This man, gifted with a keen and brilliant imagination, and possessor of a matchless talent, executed what no one else had been able to do before him; he was neither inspired by Homer, nor by Vergil; he copied no one. He learned from them only to raise himself to the poetic source, to see it where it was aud to draw from it his genius. Then he received a first inspiration and became the creator ol a particular style ol poetry which may be called romantic. Undoubtedly this style is greatly inferior to epopoeia; but after all it is original: its beauties as well as its faults belong to him.
